itfield  ."]},{"name":"Whitefield","meanings":["English: variant of   Whitfield  .","Americanized form of German <b>Weissfeld</b> (see   Weisfeld  )."]}]},{"name":"MATTHEW","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the Christian evangelist, author of the first gospel in the New Testament. His name is a form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i>, meaning ‘gift of God’, which is fairly common in the Old Testament, being rendered in the Authorized Version in a number of different forms: <i>Mattan(i)ah</i>, <i>Mattatha(h)</i>, <i>Mattithiah</i>, <i>Mattathias</i>, and so on. In the Authorized Version, the evangelist is regularly referred to as <i>Matthew</i>, while the apostle chosen to replace Judas Iscariot is distinguished as   Matthias .  A related name from the same Hebrew roots, but reversed, is   Jonathan .  Throughout the English-speaking world <i>Matthew</i> has been particularly popular since the 1970s."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathew","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Matthew ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":18,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When MATTHEW de WHITFIELD was born about 1364, in Whitfield, Northumberland, England, his father, Sir JOHN WHITFIELD, was 17 and his mother, Lady ALICE De MITFORD, was -4. He married Margaret DeLancaster in 1434. He died in 1438, in his hometown, at the age of 75."},"et":{"about 1364–1438":"umbes 1364–1438","1364–1438":"1364–1438","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","1395–Male":"1395–Surnud","1400–Male":"1400–S